{{Infobox religious building | name = Takayama Inari Shrine | native_name = 高山稲荷神社 | image = Takayama Inari Shrine.JPG | image_upright = 1.2 | caption = [[Torii]] winding through the grounds of the shrine. | map_type = Japan Aomori Prefecture#Japan | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|40.9385|140.3124|type:landmark_region:JP|display=title,inline}} | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = | deity = | founded_by = | established = | date_destroyed = | location = [[Tsugaru, Aomori|Tsugaru]], [[Aomori Prefecture|Aomori]], [[Japan]] | website = | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }} {{nihongo|'''Takayama Inari Shrine'''|高山稲荷神社 |Takayama Inari Jinja}} is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in the city of [[Tsugaru, Aomori|Tsugaru]], [[Aomori Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. The shrine is dedicated to [[Inari Ōkami]]. Takayama Inari Shrine is notable for the many red [[torii]] that wind along its path. It is said that this shrine had already been established in the late 17th century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.travel-around-japan.com/k21-14-takayama-inari.html |title=Takayama Inari Shrine (Aomori Prefecture)|website=Let's travel around Japan!}} </ref> Next to the shrine is a memorial dedicated to American sailors who died in 1889 when [[full-rigged ship]] ''[[Cheseborough]]'' wrecked off the coast of [[Shariki, Aomori|Shariki Village]] (now a part of Tsugaru) during a [[typhoon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.tsugaru.aomori.jp/English/takayama.html |title=Tsugaru City Official English Website - Tsugaru City, Aomori Prefecture, Japan |website=www.city.tsugaru.aomori.jp |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819201726/http://www.city.tsugaru.aomori.jp/English/takayama.html |archive-date=2012-08-19}} </ref>
